Req. No. 17031 Page 9

1 B. There is hereby created a cash drawer change fund for the
2 Commissioners of the Land Office. The fund shall be used as cash
3 for the Land Office to make change for customers and for the payment
4 of emergency purchases and bills. The amount held in the fund shall
5 not exceed One Thousand Dollars ($1,000.00). The initial amount in
6 the fund shall be drawn by warrant from the revolving fund created
7 pursuant to subsection A of this section. All adjustments to the
8 amount retained in the fund shall be by withdrawal and deposit in
9 the revolving fund established pursuant to subsection A of this
10 section upon the filing of a claim with proper receipts showing the
11 disbursement therefrom. Officers, employees or agents of the Land
12 Office shall be prohibited from receiving change from the fund.
13 SECTION 9. AMENDATORY 64 O.S. 2021, Section 1013, as
14 amended by Section 40, Chapter 228, O.S.L. 2022 (64 O.S. Supp. 2025,
15 Section 1013), is amended to read as follows:
16 Section 1013. A. The Commissioners of the Land Office shall be
17 responsible for the investment of the permanent school funds, other
18 educational funds, and public building funds solely in the best
19 interests of the current and future beneficiaries. The
20 Commissioners of the Land Office shall make investments:
21 1. For the exclusive purpose of:
22 a. providing maximum benefits to current and future
23 beneficiaries, and
24
Req. No. 17031 Page 10

1 b. defraying reasonable expenses of administering the
2 trust funds;
3 2. With the care, skill, prudence, and diligence under the
4 circumstances then prevailing that a prudent person acting in a like
5 enterprise of a like character and with like aims would use; and
6 3. By diversifying the investments of the trust funds so as to
7 minimize the risk of large losses.
8 B. The permanent school fund and other educational funds may
9 only be invested in bonds issued in the United States, United States
10 dollar denominated or other investments settled in United States
11 dollars or traded on the United States exchange markets, investments
12 subject to the Invest in Oklahoma Act, private equity or private
13 credit investments, and real property to be owned or acquired by the
14 Commissioners of the Land Office. The Commissioners of the Land
15 Office shall not invest more than sixty percent (60%) of the trust
16 fund investments in equity securities. The Commissioners of the
17 Land Office are further authorized to acquire, purchase, exchange,
18 and grant any real property under its their jurisdiction as is
19 necessary to carry out the investment in the real property, which
20 shall be classified specifically as investment property. The
21 Commissioners of the Land Office shall not invest more than five
22 percent (5%) of the total value of the assets of the permanent
23 school funds in connection with real property classified as
24 investments in real property. The calculation of investments in
Req. No. 17031 Page 11

1 real property within the five percent (5%) cap shall not include the
2 value of real property under long-term lease to the State of
3 Oklahoma, agencies of the state or subdivisions thereof. In no case
4 shall the Commissioners of the Land Office bid against private-
5 sector bidders above the appraised value of any property to be
6 acquired.
7 C. The Commissioners shall establish an investment committee.
8 The investment committee shall be composed of not more fewer than
9 three members of the Commissioners of the Land Office or their
10 designees. The committee shall make recommendations to the
11 Commissioners of the Land Office on all matters related to the
12 choice of managers of the assets of the funds, on the establishment
13 of investment and fund management guidelines, and in planning future
14 investment policy. The committee shall have no authority to act on
15 behalf of the Commissioners of the Land Office in any circumstances
16 whatsoever. No recommendations recommendation of the committee
17 shall have effect as an action of the Commissioners of the Land
18 Office or take effect without the approval of the Commissioners as
19 provided by law. The Commissioners shall promulgate and adopt on an
20 annual basis an investment plan. The investment plan shall state
21 the criteria for selecting investment managers, the allocation of
22 assets among investment managers, and established standards of
23 investment and fund management.
24
Req. No. 17031 Page 12

1 D. The Commissioners shall retain qualified investment managers
2 to provide for investment of the fund monies and may retain external
3 real estate property managers for the management of investment real
4 property pursuant to the investment plan. Investment managers and
5 investment property managers shall be chosen by a solicitation of
6 proposals on a competitive bid basis pursuant to standards set by
7 the Commissioners in compliance with Section 85.7 of Title 74 of the
8 Oklahoma Statutes. Subject to the investment plan, each investment
9 manager shall have full discretion in the management of the funds or
10 investment real property allocated to the investment managers each
11 manager. The funds allocated to investment managers shall be
12 actively managed by them, which may include selling investments and
13 realizing losses if the action is considered advantageous to longer
14 term return maximization. Because of the total return objective, no
15 distinction shall be made for management and performance evaluation
16 purposes between realized and unrealized capital gains and losses.
17 Subject to the investment plan, investment real estate property
18 managers shall have full discretion on leasing and operations of the
19 investment real estate under their management subject to budget
20 restrictions placed by the Commissioners of the Land Office.
21 Further, all leases pertaining to the investment real estate shall
22 be executed by the Commissioners of the Land Office upon approval by
23 the Secretary of the Land Office. Leases on investments shall be
24 exempt from term limitations for commercial property held by the
Req. No. 17031 Page 13

1 Comm issioners of the Land Office as long as the investments are
2 managed by external investment real estate property managers and the
3 lease terms are consistent with the market; however in no event
4 shall a lease on investment real estate exceed twenty-five (25)
5 years including all options. For the purposes of this section,
6 “investment real estate” means properties purchased as investments
7 and managed as part of the investment plan.
8 E. The Commissioners shall take any measures they deem
9 appropriate to safeguard custody of securities and other assets of
10 the trusts.
11 F. By September 1 of each year, the Commissioners shall develop
12 a written investment plan for the trust funds.
13 G. The Commissioners shall compile a quarterly financial report
14 showing the performance of all the combined funds under their
15 control on a fiscal year basis. The report shall contain a list of
16 all investments made by the Commissioners and a list of any
17 commissions, fees, or payments made for services regarding the
18 investments for that reporting period. The report shall be based on
19 market values and shall be compiled pursuant to uniform reporting
20 standards prescribed by the Oklahoma State Pension Commission for
21 all state retirement systems. The report shall be electronically
22 distributed to the Oklahoma State Pension Commission, the Cash
23 Management and Investment Oversight Commission, and the Legislative
24 Service Bureau.
Req. No. 17031 Page 14

1 H. Before January 1 of each year, the Commissioners shall
2 publish an annual report of all Trust trust operations, presented in
3 a simple and easily understood manner to the extent possible. The
4 report shall be submitted electronically to the Governor, the
5 Speaker of the House of Representatives, the President Pro Tempore
6 of the Senate, the State Department of Education, and each higher
7 education beneficiary. The annual report shall cover the operation
8 of the Trusts trusts during the past fiscal year including income,
9 disbursements, and the financial condition of the Trusts trusts at
10 the end of each fiscal year on a cash basis. The annual report
11 shall also contain a summary of the assets of each trust and current
12 market value as of the report date.
13 I. The Cash Management and Investment Oversight Commission
14 Invest in Oklahoma Board shall review reports prepared by the
15 Commissioners of the Land Office pursuant to this subsection
16 pertaining to their investments made in the Invest in Oklahoma
17 program and shall make recommendations regarding the investment
18 strategies and practices, the development of internal auditing
19 procedures and practices, and any other matters as determined
20 necessary and applicable.
21 J. The Commissioners of the Land Office shall select one or
22 more custodial banks to settle transactions involving the investment
23 of the funds under the control of the Commissioners of the Land
24 Office. The Commissioners of the Land Office shall review the
Req. No. 17031 Page 15

1 perf ormance of each custodial bank at least once every year. The
2 Commissioners of the Land Office shall require a written competitive
3 bid every ten (10) years. The custodial bank shall have a minimum
4 of Five Hundred Million Dollars ($500,000,000.00) in assets to be
5 eligible for selection. Any out-of-state custodial bank shall have
6 a service agent in the State of Oklahoma so that service of summons
7 or legal notice may be had on the designated agent, and the bank
8 shall submit to the jurisdiction of Oklahoma state courts for
9 resolution of any and all disputes. In order to be eligible for
10 selection, the custodial bank shall allow electronic access to all
11 transaction and portfolio reports maintained by the custodial bank
12 involving the investment of state funds under control of the
13 Commissioners of the Land Office and to the Cash Management and
14 Investment Oversight Commission. The requirement for electronic
15 access shall be incorporated into any contract between the
16 Commissioners of the Land Office and the custodial bank. Neither
17 the Commissioners of the Land Office nor the custodial bank shall
